docs.abstract: After more than 50 years and 44 National Magazine Awards, New York finds a home with a digital-media powerhouse.
docs.snippet: After more than 50 years and 44 National Magazine Awards, New York finds a home with a digital-media powerhouse.
docs.lead_paragraph: After more than 50 years of chronicling the highbrow, lowbrow, brilliant and despicable characters of the city whose name it took, New York Magazine has a new owner.

headline.main: Vox Media Acquires New York Magazine, Chronicler of the Highbrow and Lowbrow
headline.print_headline: A New Owner For New York Magazine

byline.original: By Marc Tracy and Edmund Lee

docs.abstract: The hyper-realistic movie portrays the Batman villain as a mentally ill loner looking for societal revenge. Warner Bros. said the film was not an endorsement of real-world violence.
docs.snippet: The hyper-realistic movie portrays the Batman villain as a mentally ill loner looking for societal revenge. Warner Bros. said the film was not an endorsement of real-world violence.
docs.lead_paragraph: LOS ANGELES — Warner Bros. became part of the gun safety debate again on Tuesday when relatives and friends of those killed during the 2012 movie theater shooting in Aurora, Colo., sent a letter to the studio expressing disquiet over its coming R-rated film “Joker.”

headline.main: Families of Aurora Shooting Victims Express Concern About ‘Joker’

byline.original: By Brooks Barnes and Nicole Sperling

docs.abstract: Amid worsening trade tensions, an American businessman was barred from leaving for days, in an apparent message to President Trump. Others worry they may be next.
docs.snippet: Amid worsening trade tensions, an American businessman was barred from leaving for days, in an apparent message to President Trump. Others worry they may be next.
docs.lead_paragraph: A Koch Industries executive was told he could not leave China. An ex-diplomat who helped organize a technology forum in Beijing was hassled by authorities who wanted to question him. An industry group developed contingency plans, in case its offices were raided and computer servers were seized.

headline.main: Koch Executive’s Harassment in China Adds to Fears Among Visitors
headline.print_headline: U.S. Visitors to China Are Wary Amid Accounts of Intimidation

byline.original: By Paul Mozur, Alexandra Stevenson and Edward Wong

docs.abstract: Governments are using “cyber troops” to discredit political opponents, bury opposing views and interfere in foreign affairs, according to Oxford researchers.
docs.snippet: Governments are using “cyber troops” to discredit political opponents, bury opposing views and interfere in foreign affairs, according to Oxford researchers.
docs.lead_paragraph: In Vietnam, citizens were enlisted to post pro-government messages on their personal Facebook pages. The Guatemalan government used hacked and stolen social media accounts to silence dissenting opinions. Ethiopia’s ruling party hired people to influence social media conversations in its favor.

headline.main: At Least 70 Countries Have Had Disinformation Campaigns, Study Finds
headline.print_headline: Turning to ‘Cyber Troops’ To Skew Global Reality

byline.original: By Davey Alba and Adam Satariano

docs.abstract: Disinformation experts are preparing for fast-twitch media manipulation, droves of false and misleading claims and hyper-polarized audiences fiercely clinging to their side’s version of reality.
docs.snippet: Disinformation experts are preparing for fast-twitch media manipulation, droves of false and misleading claims and hyper-polarized audiences fiercely clinging to their side’s version of reality.
docs.lead_paragraph: Even before the impeachment inquiry against President Trump was announced on Tuesday, the president’s re-election campaign blasted an email to supporters, urging them to defend Mr. Trump against the “baseless and disgusting attacks.” Facebook quickly filled with ads for impeachment-themed merchandise, including $3 “Impeach Now!” bumper stickers and $35 “Impeach This!” T-shirts. In a private chat room, pro-Trump internet trolls discussed which memes, videos and news stories to push on social media in order to reclaim the narrative.

headline.main: Brace Yourself for the Internet Impeachment

docs.abstract: The $20 million agreement over business practices in China comes a year after William Ackman’s hedge fund closed its bearish bet.
docs.snippet: The $20 million agreement over business practices in China comes a year after William Ackman’s hedge fund closed its bearish bet.
docs.lead_paragraph: Herbalife, a nutritional supplement company that was once the focus of attacks by a well-known hedge fund manager, reached a settlement on Friday with securities regulators over allegations it misled investors about its business practices in China.

headline.main: Herbalife Settles With S.E.C., but Too Late for Hedge Fund Investor
headline.print_headline: Herbalife’s S.E.C. Settlement Comes Too Late for Investor

docs.abstract: Mr. Stadler, who led Volkswagen’s Audi luxury car division, was charged in Munich with fraud and illegal advertising tied to the emissions scandal.
docs.snippet: Mr. Stadler, who led Volkswagen’s Audi luxury car division, was charged in Munich with fraud and illegal advertising tied to the emissions scandal.
docs.lead_paragraph: BERLIN — German prosecutors on Wednesday charged Rupert Stadler, former chief executive of the Audi luxury car division of Volkswagen, with fraud for the company’s role in a diesel emissions cheating scandal.

headline.main: Rupert Stadler, Ex-Audi Chief, Is Charged With Fraud in Diesel Scandal
headline.print_headline: Ex-Audi Chief Charged Over Emissions Scandal

docs.abstract: Equifax said it had exposed the data of almost 150 million people in 2017. Now it will pay at least $650 million to settle claims relating to the data breach.
docs.snippet: Equifax said it had exposed the data of almost 150 million people in 2017. Now it will pay at least $650 million to settle claims relating to the data breach.
docs.lead_paragraph: Two years after a major data breach exposed the personal information of around 147 million Americans, the credit bureau Equifax has agreed to pay at least $650 million to resolve consumer claims and multiple state and federal investigations stemming from the episode.

headline.main: Equifax Data-Breach Settlement: Get Up to $20,000 If You Can Prove Harm
headline.print_headline: ‘Flexible’ Process To Handle Claims For Consumers

docs.abstract: Russians with little experience with debt are relying on easy credit and payday lenders. Now the central bank is trying to cool the lending market.
docs.snippet: Russians with little experience with debt are relying on easy credit and payday lenders. Now the central bank is trying to cool the lending market.
docs.lead_paragraph: MOSCOW — Yekaterina V. Bulgakova gushed about the cozy one-room apartment that she and her boyfriend share, and particularly about the way they could always cover the rent: by charging it on credit card.

headline.main: Russians Pull Out Credit Cards, and Consumer Debt Spirals
headline.print_headline: Russians Fill Income Gaps With Debt

docs.abstract: The Silicon Valley company, a major government contractor, was accused of selling video surveillance software that it knew had a security issue.
docs.snippet: The Silicon Valley company, a major government contractor, was accused of selling video surveillance software that it knew had a security issue.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — Cisco Systems agreed on Wednesday to pay $8.6 million to settle claims that it sold video surveillance technology that it knew had a significant security flaw to federal, state and local government agencies.

headline.main: Cisco to Pay $8.6 Million to Settle Government Claims of Flawed Tech
headline.print_headline: Cisco Paying Millions In Flawed-Tech Case

byline.original: By Katie Benner and Kate Conger
